Title: RAY
Credit: written by
Author: brehon
Draft date: 2026-06-03
Source: a brehon story — the populated cut

FADE IN:

INT. DELANEY'S TAVERN - NIGHT

Smoke, a low jukebox, a back booth the whole room is angled toward. RAY (30s, slight, sharp) holds court over a BIG MAN in a feed cap. Beside Ray, his best friend SULLY (30s, soft, grinning) drinks it in. Across the booth, JUNE (late 20s, watchful) watches Ray the way a woman watches a thing she's decided is hers.

BIG MAN
-- somebody's got to stand up for this country.

RAY
Name the rubber company.

BIG MAN
The -- what?

RAY
The one that owns the plantations your boy's defending. The man who signed that contract won't be in any rice paddy. Neither will his sons. Yours will.

The Big Man's mouth opens. Nothing.

SULLY
(delighted)
Oh, he's done. Somebody call the widow.

Laughter. A fresh beer slides to Ray. And he turns the last of it -- softer -- to June:

RAY
Don't worry. I only do this to men who deserve it.

June laughs despite herself. The one time his words are a gift and not a knife.

And UNDER THE TABLE, unseen: Ray's right fist is white-knuckled, the whole arm trembling. A fight with nowhere to go. He presses it flat to his thigh. Stills it.

CUT TO:

EXT. THE OLD FARM - DAY

EARL (60s, a quiet man, a war behind his eyes) splits wood and says nothing. On the porch, RUTH (50s, iron) shells peas and misses nothing. TOMMY (19, big, all fire) splits beside his father; without a word Earl reaches over and fixes the boy's grip. Two of a kind.

Ray leans on the fence in a clean shirt, a book under his arm, talking -- the war, the world, the rubber companies. Earl keeps splitting. Ruth watches Ray the way you'd watch a bird that's forgotten it can fly.

RUTH
(quiet, to herself)
That one talks so he won't have to do.

CUT TO:

INT. FARM KITCHEN - MORNING

A folded Army form, squared on the oilcloth. Tommy smooths it under his thumb. Ray comes in, reads the room.

TOMMY
Went down to the courthouse.

At the stove, EARL goes very still -- a man hearing his own life come back around. Ruth's hand stops on a plate. Ray sits, and the machine starts up: the rubber companies, the casualty tables, a body's worth to the men who spend it.

Tommy turns his coffee cup, slow. Says nothing. Earl says nothing either -- but we see he could, and won't. June appears in the doorway, come for Sunday dinner, into a war.

Ray runs dry.

TOMMY
I know all that, Ray.

He stands. Goes to pack.

INT. KITCHEN - AT THE WINDOW - LATER

Tommy crosses the yard, duffel up, walking down the long road. Ray's hand rises to the cold glass and stays there. Doesn't knock. Doesn't call.

June steps up beside him, follows his eyes -- and catches something in Ray's face she has never once seen: naked, hungry, no words in front of it. It frightens her. She takes his arm. He doesn't feel it.

SMASH CUT TO:

EXT. THE OLD FARM - DAY

A government car in the lane.

RUTH takes the telegram on the porch and does not fall. She folds it once, goes inside, and starts stripping the beds. EARL walks to the woodpile and splits until dark. RAY reads it and goes cold and still and furious.

Three people, carrying the same dead boy three different ways. June reaches for Ray. He's not there.

INT. CHURCH - DAY

Rows of wet faces. One dry one: Ray. MRS. ELLIS (70s) holds his hand.

MRS. ELLIS
The Lord never sends us more than we can carry, Raymond.

RAY
He didn't send it. A man in an office did. I can get you the name.

He walks out. June watches the man she loves turn into a stranger.

INT. RAY'S PLACE - NIGHT

One bulb. Ray loads EARL'S revolver -- his father's. Calm. The hands sure.

INTERCUT -- JUNE at her dark window, awake, knowing. RUTH at the farm, sitting up in the night, also knowing. The women who feel the warriors move before they move.

EXT. RECRUITING OFFICE - DAY

Ray's car at the curb. He goes in.

INT. RECRUITING OFFICE - CONTINUOUS

A tired RECRUITER barely looks up. Ray stops inside the door, hand in his coat on the grip. In the dark glass he catches himself -- a man, squared, a hand on a gun.

Insert -- the hand inside the coat: dead steady on the revolver.
Flash -- the white-knuckled fist shaking under the tavern table.
Back -- still as stone.

Not a decision. A recognition.

RECRUITER
Help you?

Ray's hand comes out empty.

RAY
I want to sign up.

EXT. JUNE'S PORCH - DUSK

Ray's told her. June is wrecked -- and not the way he expected.

JUNE
I fell for the smartest coward in three counties. The one who'd never go. And you're standing there telling me he was never even real.

Ray -- who has a word for everything -- has none. He goes. She lets him.

SMASH CUT TO:

EXT. TRAIN PLATFORM - DAY

Ray ships out from the same boards Tommy left from. RUTH sees him off dry-eyed. EARL grips his son's hand a beat too long -- the only goodbye he owns.

EXT. FIREBASE - TREELINE - DAY (WAR)

Hell. Mortars walking the line, a SOLDIER an arm away simply gone. Ray stands in it and waits for the cold hands. They don't come. The roar drops to a held breath --

-- and he's already moving, low and sure, hauling a pinned kid, ECHOLS (18), out of the open by the webbing, the other hand putting rounds down the line. A man who's found the one tool his hands were built for.

EXT. BERM - LATER

Echols alive, sobbing into Ray's sleeve. Ray doesn't hear it. Head tipped, listening to something far off he knows.

RAY (V.O.)
(a breath)
There you are.

INTERCUT - HOME

JUNE finally opening one of his letters. SULLY in the booth, holding the floor badly from Ray's empty chair, no one really listening. RUTH and EARL on the porch at dusk, waiting, the way they have always waited.

CUT TO:

INT. DELANEY'S TAVERN - NIGHT (LATER)

Same booth. A NEW KID holds court -- Ray's own lines in a stranger's mouth.

NEW KID
-- rich man's war, poor man's funeral. Nobody in here can even name the rubber company.

SULLY sits beside him now, and when he spots Ray on a stool by the door -- older, quiet, weather in his face -- he lights up, hopeful, wanting his friend back in the chair.

NEW KID (CONT'D)
You were over there. Go on. Tell me I'm wrong.

The room leans in for the king. Ray looks at the kid a long moment -- the fast mouth, the captive jury, the safe little war you win every night without standing up. Nothing pulls.

He sets a coin on the bar, crosses, stops at the kid's shoulder.

RAY
You're not wrong. Doesn't matter. Go anyway.

He leaves Sully, the kid, the whole booth behind him.

EXT. THE OLD FARM - DAY

Ray finds EARL at the woodpile. No words. Ray takes up the second axe, and father and son split wood side by side, in the same rhythm -- the talking son become the silent one. On the porch RUTH watches, and at last lets herself cry. Not for Tommy. For the one who came home changed, the way her husband once did.

EXT. JUNE'S PORCH - DAY

Ray comes up the walk. June on the step, arms crossed, braced for the stranger.

He stops. No speech -- the words are gone for good. He just stands there, open, letting her see the whole of him with nothing out in front of it. The thing she glimpsed at the window, and now it's all there is.

A long beat.

And June -- who fell for the words -- sees the man the words were hiding the whole time, and finds she likes him better.

She uncrosses her arms.

FADE OUT.

> THE END <
